 Methodist Church]]\n| residence     = [[Artondale, Washington]]\n| alma_mater    = [[Princeton University]]<br>[[University of Oxford]]\n| website       = [http://kilmer.house.gov/ Representative Derek Kilmer]\n|}}\n\n'''Derek Christian Kilmer''' (born January 1, 1974) is an [[United States|American]] politician who has been the [[United States House of Representative|U.S. Representative]] for [[Washington's 6th congressional district]] since 2013. A [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], Kilmer previously served as a member of the [[Washington House of Representatives]] from 2005 to 2007 and as a member of the [[Washington State Senate]] from 2007 to 2013, representing the 26th district.\n\nOn March 5, 2012, Kilmer announced he was running to succeed [[Norm Dicks]] for the seat representing Washington's 6th congressional district.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://publicola.com/2012/03/05/state-sen-kilmer-running-for-us-rep-dicks-open-seat |title=State Sen. Kilmer Running for US Rep. Dicks\u2019 Open Seat}}</ref> On November 6, 2012, Kilmer won the [[general election]] to become the district's next representative.<ref>{{cite web|last=Schrader|first=Jordan|author2=Shannon, Brad|title=Democrats Derek Kilmer, Denny Heck win Congressional races|url=http://www.theolympian.com/2012/11/07/2311365/democrats-derek-kilmer-denny-heck.html|work=theolympian.com|publisher=The Olympian|accessdate=8 November 2012}}</ref> He received 186,661 votes, to opponent Bill Driscoll's 129,725.<ref>{{cite web|last=Reed|first=Sam|title=6th Congrressional District Results|url=http://vote.wa.gov/results/current/CongressionalDistrict6.html|work=2012 election results|publisher=WA STATE SEC OF STATE}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education, and business career==\nKilmer was born and raised in the [[Olympic Peninsula]], Washington. Both of his parents were public school teachers. Kilmer earned his certificate in American Studies from [[Princeton University]]. He went on to earn his BA in public affairs from Princeton's [[Woodrow Wilson School of Public and International Affairs]]. He won a [[Marshall Scholarship]] to obtain his PhD in [[Social Policy|Comparative Social Policy]] from the [[Department of Social Policy and Intervention, University of Oxford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/51516/derek-kilmer#.UaFUI5xTDKc|title=Project Vote Smart - The Voter's Self Defense System|work=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nKilmer is a former business consultant for [[McKinsey and Company]]. He was also a business retention manager for the Economic Development Board for [[Tacoma, Washington|Tacoma]]-[[Pierce County, Washington|Pierce County]]. He is also a trustee for [[Tacoma Community College]] and served on the board of Peninsula Schools Education Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.princeton.edu/paw/archive_old/PAW95-96/08_9596/0124note.html |title=Princeton Alumni Weekly&nbsp;\u2014 January 24, 1996 |publisher=Princeton University |date=1996-01-24 |accessdate=2012-03-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kilmer.house.gov/about/full-biography|title=Full Biography|publisher=|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Washington legislature==\n\n===Elections===\nIn 2004, Kilmer decided to challenge incumbent Republican State Representative Lois McMahan of Washington's 26th house district, seat 2. He defeated her 50%-48%, a difference of 1,009 votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=96953|title=Our Campaigns - WA District 26 Seat 2 Race - Nov 02, 2004|publisher=|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Republican State Senator Bob Oke decided to retire. Kilmer decided to run for Washington's 26th senate district. He defeated Republican Jim Hines 60%-40%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=206006|title=Our Campaigns - WA State Senate District 26 Race - Nov 07, 2006|publisher=|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref> In 2010, he won re-election to a second term, defeating Marty McClendon 59%-41%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=687542|title=Our Campaigns - WA State Senate District 26 Race - Nov 02, 2010|publisher=|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nIn 2007, he was one of just three Democratic state senators to vote against the bill that would allow labor unions to spend non-members' bargaining fees on political causes without first getting their permission.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/local/article/Unions-get-OK-for-political-spending-1234307.php#ixzz2ULze6Vd2|title=Unions get OK for political spending|work=seattlepi.com|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe sponsored the senate bill that would increase fines to pay for a new $849 million Tacoma Narrows bridge in his district.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.komonews.com/news/6072276.html|title=Senate approves fine for drivers who skip bridge toll|work=KOMO News|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nBusiness groups have praised Kilmer for being one of the most pro-business Democrats in Olympia. He is the three-time recipient of the \u201cLEADER Award\u201d from the Washington Economic Development Association. He was named the \"Legislative Business Star Award\" from Enterprise Washington's Business Institute. He was named \u201cLegislator of the Year\u201d by the Department of Veterans Affairs. He was recognized by the Northwest Chapter of the [[Paralyzed Veterans of America]] as \u201cLegislator of the Year\u201d. He was also named \u201cLegislator of the Year\u201d by the Washington Council of Police & Sheriffs. He was named an \"Honorary Fire Chief\" by the Washington Fire Chiefs.<ref>http://www.derekkilmer.com/about-derek/</ref>\n\n===Committee Assignments (State of Washington)===\n;Senate\n*Capital Budget Committee (Chair)\n*Economic Development, Trade, & Innovation Committee\n*Higher Education & Workforce Development Committee\n*Ways and Means Committee (Vice Chair)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ballotpedia.org/wiki/index.php/Derek_Kilmer|title=Derek Kilmer|publisher=|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===2012 election===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Washington, 2012#District 6}}\nAfter redistricting, Democratic U.S. Congressman [[Norm Dicks]] decided to retire. Kilmer decided to run for the newly redrawn [[Washington's 6th congressional district]]. He won the endorsements from [[The Seattle Times]], which called him \u201ca problem solver who can be bipartisan.\u201d [[News Tribune|The News Tribune of Tacoma]] praised him for having \u201can uncommon understanding of trade, business taxation, smart regulation, job creation and other fundamentals of economic growth.\u201d Port Angeles, Rep. Kilmer's hometown and an area for which he was elected to represent suffers from an unemployment rate 2.3 percent higher than the Washington State average, consonant with the rate of increase recorded before he took office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konp.com/local/8450|title=KONP / Local News / Unemployment rate up again in Clallam County|publisher=|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.homefacts.com/unemployment/Washington/Clallam-County/Port-Angeles.html|title=Port Angeles, WA Unemployment - Homefacts|publisher=|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref>  In the November general election, he defeated Republican nominee Bill Driscoll 59%-41%. He won all six counties in the district.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=773794|title=Our Campaigns - WA District 6 Race - Nov 06, 2012|publisher=|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/almanac/member/3533#biography|title=Login|publisher=|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Middle East Policy===\n  {{POV-section|date=June 2014}}\n\nDerek Kilmer was a cosponsor of the [[United States\u2013Israel Strategic Partnership Act of 2013]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d113:HR00938:@@@D&summ2=m&|title=Bill Summary & Status  -  113th Congress (2013 - 2014)  - H.R.938 - CRS Summary - THOMAS (Library of Congress)|publisher=|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref>  This act has been  criticized by organizations such as \"US campaign to end the Israeli occupation\"  for its unfair treatment of US citizens.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.endtheoccupation.org/|title=Blog to End the Occupation|work=Blog to End the Occupation|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nKilmer was part of a 37-member congressional delegation that visited Israel. The trip was sponsored by American Israel Education Foundation, with the intention of working to strengthen strategic economic and military cooperation between Israel and the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jewishsound.org/janis-siegel-jtnews-correspondent-38/|title=In the Middle East, a congressman learns that nothing\u2019s simple|publisher=|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Co-Sponsorship of the United States-Israel Partnership Act of 2013===\nThrough his cosponsorship of the United States-Israel Strategic Partnership Act of 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d113:HR00938:@@@D&summ2=m&|title=Bill Summary & Status  -  113th Congress (2013 - 2014)  - H.R.938 - CRS Summary - THOMAS (Library of Congress)|publisher=|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref> Rep. Kilmer supports  funding of Israel's military, and to provide assistance for cooperation in the fields of energy, water, homeland security, agriculture, and alternative fuel technologies.\n\n===Legislation===\nOn October 29, 2013, Kilmer introduced the [[American Savings Promotion Act (H.R. 3374; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would authorize some financial institutions to conduct a contest, known as a \"savings promotion [[raffle]],\" in which the sole consideration required for a chance of winning designated prizes is obtained by the deposit of a specified amount of money in a savings account or program, where each ticket or entry has an equal chance of being drawn.<ref name=3374sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 3374 - Summary|url=https://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/3374|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=ABwisniewski>{{cite news|last1=Wisniewski|first1=Mary|title=Bill to Expand Prize-Linked Savings Introduced to Congress|url=http://www.americanbanker.com/issues/178_211/bill-to-expand-prize-linked-savings-introduced-to-congress-1063318-1.html|accessdate=17 September 2014|publisher=American Banker|date=31 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Committee Assignment (US House of Representatives)===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Committee on Armed Services]]'''\n**[[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces|Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces]]\n**[[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Intelligence, Emerging Threats and Capabilities|Subcommittee on Intelligence, Emerging Threats and Capabilities]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology|Committee on Science, Space and Technology]]'''\n**[[United States House Science Subcommittee on Space|Subcommittee on Space]]\n**[[United States House Science Subcommittee on Technology|Subcommittee on Technology]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/51516/derek-kilmer#.UPdB2x37LN0|title=Project Vote Smart - The Voter's Self Defense System|work=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=19 October 2014}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://blog.thenewstribune.com/politics/2013/01/04/house-committees-denny-heck-to-financial-services-derek-kilmer-to-science-space-technology/|title=House committees: Denny Heck to Financial Services, Derek Kilmer to Science, Space &  Technology|work=Tacoma News Tribune|accessdate=19 October 2014}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://public.cq.com/docs/news/news-000004172493.html|title=CQ - 113th Congress: Derek Kilmer, D-Wash. (6th District)|publisher=|accessdate=19 October 2014}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.theolympian.com/2012/11/07/2311365/democrats-derek-kilmer-denny-heck.html|title=Local News - The Olympian|publisher=|accessdate=19 October 2014}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2019621639_elexcongresslocal07m.html|title=Democratic state Sen. Kilmer wins race to replace U.S. Rep. Dicks|work=The Seattle Times|accessdate=19 October 2014}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://kilmer.house.gov/ Congressman Derek Kilmer] official U.S. House website\n*[http://kilmerforcongress.com/ Derek Kilmer for Congress]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Washington/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Derek_Kilmer_%5BD-6%5D}}\n*{{CongLinks | congbio = K000381 | ballot = Derek_Kilmer | nndb = | votesmart = 51516 | govtrack = 412583 | opencong = 412583 | rollcall = 46051 | politifact = | fec = H2WA06129 | opensecrets = N00034453 | assets = | legistorm = | followthemoney = 7288 | ontheissues = House/Derek_Kilmer.htm | congress = derek-kilmer/2169 | worldcat = lccn-nr2004-7402 | cspan = 68310 | imdb = | bloomberg = | nyt = | washpo = 3518ebbc-4bb7-11e2-8758-b64a2997a921 }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox |\n  state=Washington|\n  district=6 |\n  before=[[Norm Dicks]] |\n  start=January 3, 2013\n}}\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dan Kildee]]<br><small>D-[[Michigan]]</small>}}\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]''|years=392nd}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ann McLane Kuster]]<br><small>D-[[New Hampshire]]</small>}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{WA-FedRep}}\n\n{{Persondata \n| NAME              = Kilmer, Derek\n| ALTERNATIVE NAMES =\n| SHORT DESCRIPTION = American politician\n| DATE OF BIRTH     = January 1, 1974\n| PLACE OF BIRTH    = Olympic Peninsula, Washington, United States\n| DATE OF DEATH     =\n| PLACE OF DEATH    